<h2 id="setting-up-branded-reports">Setting Up Branded Reports</h2>

<p>Setting up white-label reports properly takes more than uploading your logo. Here is a practical guide to creating branded reports that look professional and serve your client relationships well.</p>

<p><strong>Brand assets preparation:</strong> Before configuring any tool, prepare your brand assets. You need a high-resolution logo (PNG with transparent background, minimum 500px wide), your primary and secondary brand colours as hex codes, your agency name as it should appear in reports, your website URL, and your contact email or phone number. Having these ready before starting configuration prevents the back-and-forth that slows setup down.</p>

<p><strong>Report template customisation:</strong> Most white-label tools allow you to choose which sections appear in your report. Do not include everything. Tailor the report to the client's technical understanding. For non-technical business owners, include: Health Score trend, top 5 critical issues with plain-language explanations, a comparison to the previous reporting period, and your prioritised recommendations. For technical clients (in-house development teams), include: full issue lists with affected URLs, severity breakdown, structured data validation, and performance metrics.</p>

<p><strong>Adding your own commentary:</strong> The automated audit data is commodity information. What makes your report valuable is your interpretation and recommendations. Most white-label tools allow you to add custom text sections. Use these to write an executive summary that translates technical findings into business impact. For example, instead of "47 pages have duplicate title tags", write "47 pages are competing with each other in Google search because they share identical titles. This is diluting your ranking potential for key revenue-driving keywords. We recommend making each title unique, starting with the 12 product category pages that drive the most organic traffic."</p>

<p><strong>Automated scheduling:</strong> Set up reports to generate and email to clients on a consistent schedule. Monthly is standard for most retainer clients. The reports should arrive on the same date each month, ideally a few days before your scheduled client call so the client has time to review them. Configure the email delivery to come from your agency email address if the tool supports custom sender addresses.</p>

<p><strong>Client dashboard setup:</strong> If your tool supports branded dashboards (SE Ranking, AgencyAnalytics, WebCEO), set up client login portals. Map the dashboard to a subdomain on your agency's domain (e.g., reports.youragency.com). This reinforces your brand and gives clients real-time access to their data between reports. Set appropriate permission levels so clients can view data but not modify settings or access other clients' data.</p>

<h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>

<p>The cost of white-label auditing varies dramatically depending on the tool and the number of clients you manage. Here is a realistic cost analysis for different agency sizes.</p>

<p><strong>Solo freelancer (1-3 clients):</strong> Sitechecker at $49/month or AgencyAnalytics at $79/month provides adequate white-label reporting at the lowest cost. SE Ranking at $65/month (Essential) gives you a better audit engine but limited white-label features. At 1-3 clients paying $500-1,500/month each for SEO services, tool costs represent a small fraction of revenue.</p>

<p><strong>Small agency (4-10 clients):</strong> SE Ranking Pro at $119/month is the sweet spot. It provides 5 projects with white-label reports, a branded client dashboard, and an audit engine that catches all critical issues. The cost per client is roughly $12-30/month, which is easily absorbed into retainer pricing. If you need more data depth, adding Screaming Frog at £199/year for deep-dive audits keeps the total annual tool cost under $1,700.</p>

<p><strong>Mid-size agency (11-25 clients):</strong> SE Ranking Business at $259/month or Semrush Guru at $249.95/month (note: Guru does not include white-label, which requires Business at $499.95/month). If white-label is essential, SE Ranking remains the better value. If you can work with Semrush's standard branding and add your commentary manually, the Guru plan's broader toolkit may be worth the trade-off.</p>

<p><strong>Large agency (25+ clients):</strong> At this scale, Semrush Business at $499.95/month makes sense because the per-client cost drops below $20 and the breadth of the platform (keyword research, backlink analysis, competitive intelligence, content tools) supports the full range of agency services. Custom enterprise pricing is available from SE Ranking, AgencyAnalytics, and WebCEO for agencies with 25+ clients.</p>

<p>When evaluating pricing, calculate the cost per client and compare it to the time saved versus manual reporting. If a white-label tool saves you 2 hours per client per month on reporting, and your billable rate is $100/hour, a $119/month tool that serves 5 clients is saving you $1,000/month in time. The ROI is immediate.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-sell-audit-services">How to Sell Audit Services</h2>

<p>A website audit tool is not just a diagnostic instrument for existing clients. It is a powerful sales tool for winning new business. Here is how successful agencies use audits to generate revenue.</p>

<p><strong>The free prospecting audit:</strong> Run a quick audit of a prospect's site before your sales call. Generate a branded one-page summary showing their Health Score, top 3 critical issues, and a brief explanation of the business impact. Present this in the sales meeting as "we ran a preliminary health check on your site." This demonstrates competence, creates urgency (the prospect now knows they have problems), and positions your agency as the solution. The cost of running the audit is negligible. The conversion rate improvement is significant.</p>

<p><strong>The paid comprehensive audit:</strong> Offer a standalone comprehensive audit as a productised service, typically priced at $500-2,500 depending on site size and complexity. The deliverable is a detailed branded report with prioritised recommendations, estimated effort for each fix, and expected business impact. This serves two purposes: it generates immediate revenue and it acts as a gateway to a monthly retainer. Once the client sees the full scope of work needed, they often convert to ongoing SEO services.</p>

<p><strong>The monthly retainer audit:</strong> Include regular audit reports as part of your ongoing SEO retainer. The monthly Health Score trend demonstrates the value of your work and justifies the retainer fee. When the score improves, you show that your work is having a measurable impact. When new issues appear, you show that your monitoring caught problems early before they affected rankings. Either way, the audit supports client retention.</p>

<p><strong>Packaging and pricing:</strong> Structure your audit offerings in tiers. A basic audit (automated report with a brief summary) can be offered at a low price point or free as a lead generator. A standard audit (automated report plus manual review and prioritised recommendations) is your primary paid product. A premium audit (comprehensive manual review, competitive benchmarking, and implementation roadmap) is your highest-value offering. White-label tools make the basic and standard tiers scalable because the report generation is automated.</p>

<p><strong>Scaling with automation:</strong> Set up automated prospecting audits for lists of potential clients. Some tools allow batch auditing of multiple domains. Run audits on businesses in your target market, generate one-page branded summaries for each, and use these as personalised outreach collateral. A cold email that includes "We audited your website and found 3 critical issues affecting your Google rankings" performs significantly better than generic outreach because it demonstrates specific value upfront.</p>

<p><strong>Upselling from audits:</strong> Every audit finding is a potential service offering. Broken links lead to a technical fix-up project. Thin content leads to a content writing engagement. Missing structured data leads to a schema implementation project. Performance issues lead to a speed optimisation project. The audit provides a roadmap of billable work. Position your audit as the diagnostic step that defines the treatment plan, and the treatment plan as the ongoing services you provide.</p>

<p>White-label auditing transforms a commodity SaaS tool into a branded, revenue-generating asset for your agency. The tools described in this guide provide the technical foundation. Your agency's expertise, presentation, and client relationships provide the value that commands premium pricing.</p>

